# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2009-national-league-division-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] It played in the National Association league in 1875 and in the National League from 1876 to 1877.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] After a scandal over game-fixing, combined with financial problems, the St Louis Brown Stockings left the National League but continued to play as an independent team from 1878 to 1881.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Chris von der Ahe, a German immigrant, purchased the team prior to the 1882 season and joined the new American Association.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings posted a 37-43 game record in their first season in the American Association, giving them fifth place.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team played at the Grand Avenue Grounds (which was later renamed Sportsman's Park) at the corner of Grand Avenue and Dodier Street in north St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Before the 1882 season, Von der Ahe secured a place for the team in the American Association and provided funds to bring players to St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Between 1882 and 1892, the team he built went on to win four American Association titles.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Al Spink, the team advisor, recommended Von der Ahe sign Charlie Comiskey.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Comiskey, who later played with the Chicago White Sox, was a skilled, young, first baseman who had been playing in Dubuque, Iowa.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Ned Cuthbert was a former professional player in St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Although he had retired from baseball and worked as a bartender in St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis, Cuthbert remained prominent in the local baseball community.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He had encouraged Von der Ahe to purchase the team.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Von der Ahe hired Cuthbert to be his first captain, with all the duties of a field manager.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Cuthbert used his experience to attract several players to St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Most of the first-year Browns originated in St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis, including brothers Jack and Bill Gleason, pitcher Jumbo McGinnis, outfielder George Seward, and catcher Tom Sullivan.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In 1866, Gus Solari laid out a professional baseball field at Sportsman's Park, St Louis.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Sixteen years later, on May 2, 1882, the opening day of the St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings' 1882 season took place.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Approximately 2,000 spectators watched the game for a fee of one quarter each.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team played numerous local teams in April exhibitions.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] McGinnis was the first pitcher and he started 45 of the team's 80 games.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] It was a lead off single in the first innings.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He also scored the first run on Comiskey's three-base hit.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team won their first game with a score of 9 runs to 7.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In late May 1882, the team was in a tie for first place in its six-team league.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They were eight games over .500, putting them one game behind the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] There followed a seven-week period when the team lost sixteen more games than they won.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They could not contend for the championship.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] During the season, more than 175,000 spectators attended the team's games.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The favorite players on the team were Comiskey and McGinnis.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] The Brooklyn baseball club was formed in 1883 by real estate magnate and baseball enthusiast Charles Byrne who convinced his brother-in-law Joseph Doyle and casino operator Ferdinand Abell to start the team with him.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] Byrne set up a grandstand on fifth avenue and named it Washington Park in honor of George Washington.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] The team played in the minor Inter-State Association of Professional Baseball Clubs.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] Doyle became the first manager of the team, which drew 6,000 fans to its first home game on May 12, 1883, against the Trenton team.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] (This was actually the second game the club played in Brooklyn; three days earlier, with Washington Park not yet ready, the Greys beat Harrisburg 7–1 at the Parade Ground.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] It was the only professional match ever held at the ground, with some 2,000 fans in attendance.) The team won the league title after the **Camden Merritt** club disbanded on July 20 and Brooklyn picked up some of its better players.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] The Grays were invited to join the American Association for the following season.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The 1883 season was the first in the history of the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The team was founded earlier in the year as a replacement for the Worcester franchise.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] It was the first year Philadelphia was represented in the National League since the original Athletics were disbanded in 1876 after refusing to finish the season.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The American Association's Philadelphia Athletics had been founded a year earlier.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The team opened the year managed by Bob Ferguson; however, he was fired as manager after a disappointing 4–13 start and replaced by Blondie Purcell.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The team finished the season 17–81, worst in the National League.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies played their first game ever on April 2, 1883, and defeated the amateur Manayunk Ashlands in an exhibition game by the score of 11–0 at Recreation Park.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies hosted Providence at Recreation Park in their first regular season game on May 1, 1883.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] One thousand fans saw John Coleman start the game for the Phillies and relinquish the first hit in the first inning to Providence first baseman Joe Start.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies scored first and took a three to zero lead into the eighth inning when Providence scored four times to win the game.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies would lose their first eleven games, and not win their first game at home in Philadelphia until June 6, 1883.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's second season in St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri and its second season in the American Association.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1883-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 65–33 during the season and finished second in the American Association.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The **1884 Brooklyn Atlantics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] It was the first season in the American Association for the team, and they finished the year in ninth place.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The Brooklyn baseball team had played as the **Brooklyn Grays** in the Interstate Association in 1883, where they won the championship.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] In 1884, Charles Byrne moved the team into the American Association, renaming them the Atlantics in tribute to the old National Association Brooklyn Atlantics team.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The **2009 National League Division Series** (**NLDS**) consisted of two concurrent best-of-five game series on the National League side in Major League Baseball’s 2009 postseason that determined the participating teams in the 2009 National League Championship Series.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Three divisional winners and a "wild card" team played in the two series.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The NLDS began on Wednesday, October 7 and ended on Monday, October 12.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] TBS televised all games in the United States.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] This marked the second postseason meeting between the Phillies and Rockies in three seasons; the Rockies swept the Phillies in the 2007 NLDS.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The Dodgers and Cardinals last met in the postseason during the 2004 NLDS, which the Cardinals won 3–1.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The Dodgers and Phillies won their respective series—the Dodgers three games to none and the Phillies three games to one.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The Phillies defeated the Dodgers in the NLCS by a series score of 4–1, and lost the 2009 World Series to the American League champion New York Yankees, 4–2.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Neither team's starting pitcher was particularly effective in the series opener; however, neither team's offense was able to capitalize, as this game set an MLB postseason record for runners left on base combined between the two teams, with 30.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Los Angeles starter Randy Wolf loaded the bases with no outs in the first inning, but allowed just one run on Ryan Ludwick's one-out single.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Louis starter Chris Carpenter gave up a two-run home run to Matt Kemp, giving the Dodgers a lead they would never relinquish.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the third, they put runners on first and second on a walk and hit-by-pitch before Casey Blake's RBI single put them up 3–1.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The Cardinals cut the lead back to one in the fourth when Colby Rasmus drew a leadoff walk, moved to second on a groundout and scored on Skip Schumaker's double.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the fifth, Rafael Furcal's sacrifice fly with runners on second and third made it 4–2 Dodgers.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Next inning, Kyle McClellan hit Russell Martin with a pitch with the bases loaded to force in another run, charged to Dennys Reyes, for the Dodgers.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the top of the ninth, Jonathan Broxton allowed a one-out single to Ryan Ludwick, who scored on Mark DeRosa's two-out double, before striking out Rick Ankiel looking to end the game and give the Dodgers a 1–0 series lead.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Los Angeles slugger Manny Ramirez was held to 1-for-4 with one walk, while St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Louis slugger Albert Pujols was 0-for-3 with two intentional walks.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The game ran 3:54 which made it the longest nine-inning postseason game in history: however, the record was broken four days later by the Rockies and Phillies.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In an amazing pitching duel, Game 2 was dominated by Cardinals pitcher Adam Wainwright and Dodgers phenom Clayton Kershaw, who was pitching in his first career postseason start.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the second inning, Matt Holliday hit a home run to put the Cardinals ahead 1–0, but Dodger slugger Andre Ethier hit his first career post-season homer to tie it up 1–1 in the bottom of the fourth, the first hit Wainwright allowed.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Wainwright dominated throughout his start, retiring the first 11 hitters he faced, while Kershaw kept pitching in and out of trouble.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the seventh inning, a double by Colby Rasmus with no outs scored Mark DeRosa to put St.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Louis ahead 2–1, but Rasmus was thrown out at third base, which ended up being a huge play.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] At the time, it seemed to be enough to allow Wainwright to pitch to victory; in the eighth inning, however, he pitched into a bases-loaded jam.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] With two outs, Game 1 hero Matt Kemp grounded out to Albert Pujols to end the threat, and going into the ninth inning, Cardinal closer Ryan Franklin was brought in with one out.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] After retiring Manny Ramirez, Dodger first baseman James Loney hit a fly ball to Holliday, who lost the ball in the lights and it hit off his belly, allowing Loney to reach second on the error.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The Dodgers swept the Cardinals 3–0, and went on to go face the Phillies in a NLCS rematch.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Vicente Padilla silenced the Cardinals' bats again by pitching dominantly, allowing no runs on four hits through seven innings.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The 47,296 attendance was the largest crowd to see a game at Busch Stadium since it opened in 2006.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the top of the first, Matt Kemp singled with one out off Joel Piñeiro and scored on Manny Ramirez's two-out double.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the third, Andre Ethier's two-run home run made it 3–0 Dodgers.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Next inning, Ronnie Belliard hit a leadoff single, moved to second on a groundout, and scored on Rafael Furcal's two-out single.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the seventh, Ethier tripled with two outs off John Smoltz and scored on Ramirez's single.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The Cardinals scored their only run of the game in the eighth when Julio Lugo walked off George Sherrill, stole second and scored on Albert Pujols's single off Jonathan Broxton.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Broxton pitched a scoreless ninth to seal the series for the Dodgers.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Amidst strong, swirling winds at Citizens Bank Park, the Phillies cruised to a 5–1 victory behind a dominating performance from Cliff Lee.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Philadelphia broke a scoreless tie in the bottom of the fifth when Jayson Werth drew a leadoff walk and scored on an RBI double by Raúl Ibañez, who scored two batters later on a single from Carlos Ruiz.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Rockies starter Ubaldo Jiménez ran into more trouble in the sixth, giving up a leadoff single to Chase Utley, who stole second, then an RBI double to Jayson Werth and an RBI triple to Ryan Howard.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Joe Beimel relieved Jimenez and allowed an RBI single to Ibanez.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Lee, meanwhile, retired 16 straight Colorado batters from the second inning into the seventh, picking up the complete game win in his first career postseason start.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Lee was one strike away from completing a shutout, but Troy Tulowitzki lined a two-out, two-strike double in the top of the ninth to score Carlos Gonzalez from first to plate the Rockies' only run.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Actor Kevin Bacon and his brother Michael sang the national anthem before the game.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] 2008 NLCS and World Series MVP Cole Hamels faced Rockies' starter Aaron Cook in Game 2.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the top of the first inning, the Rockies scored the first run of the game when Todd Helton hit a ball up the first base line that was misplayed by Hamels allowing Carlos Gonzalez to score from third.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Rockies' catcher Yorvit Torrealba then hit a two-run home run off Hamels in the fourth inning after he had not hit a home run since May 6.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the next inning, Dexter Fowler's sacrifice fly with runners on second and third made it 4–0 Rockies.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Hamels was then told his wife, who was 9 months pregnant, was going into labor and he was lifted for a pinch-hitter in the bottom of the fifth inning.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The Phillies would then fight back in the sixth inning.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] After consecutive hits by Shane Victorino and Chase Utley put runners on first and second with nobody out, Ryan Howard hit a line-drive double into the right field corner making the score 4–1.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Jose Contreras relieved Cook as Raúl Ibañez hit a one-out single to center field scoring two runs to cut the score to 4–3.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Pedro Feliz's single then loaded the bases, but Carlos Ruiz grounded into a double play, ending the threat.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Charlie Manuel would use potential Game 3 starters Joe Blanton and J.A.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Happ in the seventh inning, with Happ only throwing four pitches and leaving with an injury after being hit on the leg by a ball.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The Rockies loaded the bases before Fowler's sacrifice fly off Scott Eyre made it 5–3 Rockies.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Jayson Werth hit a home run in the eighth inning off Rafael Betancourt to once again close the Rockies lead to 1, but Huston Street retired Shane Victorino with two runners on base with two outs in the ninth inning to send the series to Colorado tied 1–1.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Game 3 was originally scheduled for October 10 at 9:37 p.m.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Eastern, but was postponed due to snowy weather in the Denver area.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The city received two inches of snow by Saturday morning, and forecasts called for a game-time temperature of 26 °F (−3 °C).
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The October 10 low was 17 °F (−8 °C), breaking a record set in 1905.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] This normally would not have been a problem due to Coors Field's underground heating system, and the Rockies have played in freezing conditions before.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] However, MLB began giving serious thought to postponing the game after hearing that the temperature would barely make it above freezing, and reports of icy roads and numerous accidents clinched the decision.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] This pushed Game 4 back to October 12, with Game 5, if necessary, to be played the next day in Philadelphia with no travel day.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The temperature at game time (10:07 pm Eastern; 8:07 pm local) was 35 °F (2 °C) and it dropped over the course of the game, which ended after midnight local time.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Chase Utley's two-out home run off Jason Hammel made it 1–0 Phillies in the first, but in the bottom half, Todd Helton's RBI groundout after back-to-back leadoff singles off J.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] After a single and strikeout, Garrett Atkins's RBI single put the Rockies up 2–1.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the third, Helton drew a leadoff walk and scored on Atkins's double to make it 3–1 Rockies, but in the fourth, a leadoff walk and single was followed by Ryan Howard's RBI single.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Hammel then walked two to load the bases and force in another run to tie the game.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] After a double play, Carlos Ruiz's RBI single put the Phillies up 4–3, but Carlos Gonzalez's home run in the bottom of the inning off Joe Blanton tied the game.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the sixth, back-to-back one-out walks off Jose Contreras were followed by Ruiz's RBI single that put the Phillies up 5–4.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the bottom of the seventh, Scott Eyre allowed a leadoff double and subsequent single before being relieved by Ryan Madson, who allowed a one-out sacrifice fly to Troy Tulowitzki to tie the game.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the ninth, Ryan Howard's sacrifice fly with two on off Huston Street put the Phillies up 6–5.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Brad Lidge pitched a scoreless bottom half despite allowing two walks to give the Phillies a 2–1 series lead.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Game 4 was originally scheduled to start on Game 3's date and start time, but due to the Saturday postponement was pushed back to Monday with first pitch at 4:07 Mountain Time.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] With an extra day of rest, both teams pitched their aces in a rematch of Game 1.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The Phillies quickly struck in the first, as the second batter of the game, Shane Victorino, hit a home run into the Rockies bullpen.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Jimenez would settle down, virtually matching the Phillies' Cliff Lee the rest of the way, his only other run coming on a Jayson Werth homer in the sixth.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Lee wasn't as dominant as he was in Game 1, but held the Rockies at bay until the sixth when he walked Todd Helton on four pitches and Troy Tulowitzki doubled him home to cut the lead to 2–1.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] He got out of it by getting Garrett Atkins to line out to third, and Tulowitzki was doubled off second.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Jimenez pitched seven innings before giving way to Franklin Morales.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] The Phillies would load the bases in the eighth with one out off Morales, but Rafael Betancourt would get a pop out and strikeout to keep Philadelphia from adding to their lead.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] With one out in the bottom of the inning, Lee walked Dexter Fowler.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Helton then bounced what looked like a tailor-made double play ground ball to Chase Utley.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Fowler, to avoid running into him, jumped and hurdled over Utley, whose throw to second was wide and an error.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Lee was pulled and a double switch was made, Ryan Madson in to pitch, Ben Francisco in left field.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Tulowitzki promptly stepped up and hit a shallow fly to left that Francisco made a diving catch on to rob the Rockies of the potential tying run.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Jason Giambi pinch hit, and on the first pitch punched a game-tying single to left.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Yorvit Torrealba followed by hitting a two-run double over the head of Victorino, giving the Rockies their first lead.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Madson then intentionally walked Seth Smith and threw a wild pitch to advance both runners, but got Clint Barmes to ground out to end the inning.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] In the ninth Colorado again turned to Street, the losing pitcher in Game 3 to send the series back to Philadelphia for a Game 5.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] This time he opened the inning by striking out pinch hitter Greg Dobbs, prompting Ryan Howard to tell his teammates to "get me to the plate, boys." Jimmy Rollins, though, as he did the previous night, singled.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] After Victorino bounced into a fielder's choice that saw Rollins forced out at second, Utley stepped up and went down 2–2 in the count.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] He would, however, work a walk to bring go-ahead run Ryan Howard to the plate.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] On a 2–1 pitch, Howard belted a double to the wall in right field, tying the game.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Werth followed with a bloop single to shallow right on a 2–2 pitch as the Phillies matched the Rockies' three-run rally with one of their own to retake the lead.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Colorado would threaten again in the ninth against Scott Eyre.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] With one out, Carlos Gonzalez singled, tying him with Dante Bichette for the club record for hits in the Division Series at ten.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Following a Fowler lineout, Helton singled up middle.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Brad Lidge was again summoned from the bullpen and faced Tulowitzki in a rematch of the previous night's final at-bat.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] Having looked at two sliders, and barely checked his swing on another, Lidge threw Tulowitzki a 2–2 slider.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] This time Tulowitzki could not check his swing, striking out to end the game, and sending the Phillies to the NLCS with a three-games-to-one series victory.
[src:2009-national-league-division-series/2009-national-league-division-series] It also marked the first time in Division Series history that all four series winners clinched on the road, as the Dodgers, Angels and Yankees all had completed sweeps on the road previously.
